    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-07-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-07-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="833"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d833">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Lauchlin Currie</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="31a" xml:id="d833fn31a">Administrative Assistant to President
                        Roosevelt.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">to President <persName type="to">Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="32" type="source" xml:id="d833fn32">Photostatic copy obtained from the
                        Franklin D. Roosevelt Library, Hyde Park, N. Y. Notation in ink by President
                        Roosevelt: “L. C. OK FDR”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-07-11">July 11,
                            1941</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="flushleft">Re: Reply to Chiang Kai-shek’s message.</p>
                <p>In accordance with your instructions, I discussed this matter with Mr. Welles. He
                    suggests that you authorize me to convey the following message to T. V.
                    Soong:</p>
                <p>In answer to the Generalissimo’s enquiry as to whether the President would be in
                    favor of definite military arrangements between the Soviet and Chinese
                    Governments, the President has authorized me to inform <pb facs="1014" n="1006"
                        xml:id="pg_1006"/> you that the United States Government, not being a party
                    to the agreement, cannot take responsibility for it. However, the President
                    added that he was of the opinion that such military arrangements would
                    definitely be to China’s benefit. His attitude toward the suggested pact between
                    China, Russia and Great Britain was similar. The President would appreciate
                    further information as to the nature of the proposed military arrangements and
                    pact.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lauchlin Currie</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
